04580nam a22007575i 9780231522724DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20102010nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2009041198  a(OCoLC)979753935  a97802315227247 a10.7312/keen151462doi  a(DE-B1597)458993  a(OCoLC)676814340  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPL723b.K42 2010 4aPL723b.K42 2010eb 7aHIS0210002bisacsh04a940.53 5209222221 aKeene, Donald, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSo Lovely a Country Will Never Perish :bWartime Diaries of Japanese Writers /cDonald Keene. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAsia Perspectives: History, Society, and Culture00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction: Wartime Diaries -- t1. The Day the War Began -- t2. The Birth of “Greater East Asia” -- t3. False Victories and Real Defeats -- t4. A Dismal New Year -- t5. On the Eve -- t6. The Jade Voice -- t7. The Days After -- t8. The Revival of Literature -- t9. Rejection of the War -- t10. Under the Occupation -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe attack on Pearl Harbor, which precipitated the Greater East Asia War and its initial triumphs, aroused pride and a host of other emotions among the Japanese people. Yet the single year in which Japanese forces occupied territory from Alaska to Indonesia was followed by three years of terrible defeat. Nevertheless, until the shattering end of the war, many Japanese continued to believe in the invincibility of their country. But in the diaries of well-known writersincluding Nagai Kafu, Takami Jun, Yamada Futaru, and Hirabayashi Taikoand the scholar Watanabe Kazuo, varying doubts were vividly, though privately, expressed.Donald Keene, renowned scholar of Japan, selects from these diaries, some written by authors he knew well. Their revelations were sometimes poignant, sometimes shocking to Keene. Ito Sei's fervent patriotism and even claims of racial superiority stand in stark contrast to the soft-spoken, kindly man Keene knew. Weaving archival materials with personal recollections and the intimate accounts themselves, Keene reproduces the passions aroused during the war and the sharply contrasting reactions in the year following Japan's surrender. Whether detailed or fragmentary, these entries communicate the reality of false victory and all-too-real defeat.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAuthors, Japanesey20th centuryvDiaries. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945vPersonal narratives, Japanese. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xLiterature and the war. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zJapan. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/keen1514640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231522724423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231522724/original  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK